a  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Grassia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Amedeo, Maurizio, Pasquale, Rocco, Salvatore.","Italian: from a metathesized form of the personal name<i>Garsia</i>, from Spanish <i>García</i> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Arcia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Alberto, Francisco, Arturo, Dagoberto, Enrique, Jose, Ramiro, Adalberto, Aleida, Alejandro, Alfredo, Amalia.","Hispanic: probably an altered form of Spanish <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Garcie","meanings":["Altered form, under the French influence in LA, of Spanish <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  ). This form of the surname of Spanish origin is also found in southern France.","Spanish (Ávila): variant of <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Garcilazo","meanings":["Hispanic (mainly Mexico and Argentina): altered form of Spanish (Valencia) <b>Garcilaso</b>, a compound of the personal name <i>Garci</i> (a short form of <i>García</i>, see   Garcia  ) and the nickname <i>laso</i> ‘weak, exhausted’."]},{"name":"Gacia","meanings":["Hispanic: altered form of Spanish <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Garsia","meanings":["Hispanic: altered form of   Garcia  ."]},{"name":"Gracia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Juan, Manuel, Francisco, Jesus, Luis, Guadalupe, Mario, Pedro, Javier, Jorge.","Spanish; Catalan (<b>Gràcia</b>): from a short form of the Christian religious epithet <i>de la Gracia</i>, meaning ‘of mercy’ and forming part of the Marian name <i>Maria de la Gracia</i> ‘(Holy) Mary of Grace’, from Spanish <i>gracia</i>, Catalan <i>gràcia</i> ‘grace, mercy’.","In some cases possibly also an altered form of Spanish <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"De Garcia","meanings":["Spanish and Galician (<b>De García</b>); Portuguese: patronymic from Spanish and Galician <b>García</b> and Portuguese   Garcia  , with the preposition <i>de</i> ‘of’."]},{"name":"Garces","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jorge, Carlos, Juan, Jose, Manuel, Cesar, Rafael, Luis, Fernando, Gustavo, Javier, Mario.  Portuguese Albeiro, Paulo.","Spanish; Catalan (<b>Garcés</b>); Portuguese (<b>Garcês</b>): patronymic from the personal name <i>García</i> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Garzia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Mario, Alfredo, Ernestina, Fernando, Juan, Pedro, Ricardo.  Italian Angelo, Antonio, Ciro, Corrado.","Italianized form of Spanish   Garcia  ."]}]},{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Braganza","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Portuguese <b>Bragança</b>: habitational name from the city of Bragança in northern Portugal. This form of the surname is most common in India, as a result of former Portuguese colonization of the western coast of this country, and in the Philippines.","History: <i>Braganza</i> is an Anglicized form of the name of the royal house <i>Bragança</i> whose members occupied the throne of Portugal from 1640 to 1910. Before that, they exercised enormous power in the Iberian peninsula as Dukes of Braganza from 1442 onward."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Elvira","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["name of Germanic (Visigothic) origin , very common in the Middle Ages. It was not used in the English-speaking world until the 19th century, when it was made familiar as the name of the long-suffering wife of  Don Juan , both in  Mozart's  opera Don Giovanni (  1789 ) and in  Byron's  satirical epic poem Don Juan (  1819–24 ). In his comedy Blithe Spirit  Noel Coward  used it as the name of  Charles Condomine's  first wife, who returns to haunt him. It is also the name of the heroine of the Swedish film Elvira Madigan (  1967 ), directed by  Bo Widerberg , a romantic tragedy about a pair of lovers who would rather die than be separated."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Elvira García De Braganza was born as the daughter of Garcia Pires de Braganca and Gontinha Soares de Tougues. She had at least 4 sons and 4 daughters with Ordoño Alvarez de las Asturias y Nava."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1206–1238":"1206–1238","–Female":"Surnud","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1195–Male":"1195–Surnud","1206–1261":"1206–1261","1225–1280":"1225–1280","–1251":"–1251","–Male":"Surnud","1155–1206":"1155–1206","1152–Female":"1152–Surnud","1175":"1175","1152":"1152","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","1261":"1261","1150":"1150","aproximadamente 1225":"umbes 1225","1280":"1280","1180":"1180","1206":"1206","1238":"1238","1225":"1225","1640":"1640","1155":"1155","Asturias, España":"Asturias, Hispaania","Spain":"Hispaania"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1175–Male":"1175–Kuollut","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1185–Female":"1185–Kuollut","1206–1238":"1206–1238","–Female":"Kuollut","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollut","1195–Male":"1195–Kuollut","1206–1261":"1206–1261","1225–1280":"1225–1280","–1251":"–1251","–Male":"Kuollut","1155–1206":"1155–1206","1152–Female":"1152–Kuollut","1175":"1175","1152":"1152","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","1261":"1261","1150":"1150","aproximadamente 1225":"noin 1225","1280":"1280","11